In this nebula lies the brightest group of young stars in our Milky Way.
This star-forming region is constantly producing new stars.
In this cloud of stars, associated with the Rosette Nebula, new stars are also continuously forming; 5,000 light years away from Earth.
In this bright galaxy with a small black hole there is no dust yet, only gas.
Researchers hypothesize that it formed shortly after the Big Bang, when the universe was mostly composed of hydrogen.
Our window to the universe: the most important telescopes
It appears that the telescope was invented by Hans Lipperhey in 1608, before Galileo Galilei used it a year later to observe the stars.
Since then, the mirrors of optical telescopes have been growing steadily and the images they provide are becoming increasingly detailed.
For 30 years, from 1947 to 1975, the Hale Telescope located at the Palomar Observatory near San Diego was the largest in the world.
The mirror in the picture had a diameter of five meters.
In Arizona, USA, the Large Binocular Telescope stands.
This allows us to observe the cosmos through two mirrors, each with a diameter of 8.4 meters.
The interior of the Gran Telescopio Canarias located on the island of La Palma is huge - the mirror alone has a diameter of 10.4 meters.
The mirror of the Southern African Large Telescope in South Africa is segmented to save costs.
Despite this, it reaches a diameter of approximately eleven meters.
The drawback of this cheaper construction is that the telescope has a fixed elevation angle, so its mobility is limited.
The Hobby-Eberly Telescope in Texas also has a fixed elevation angle.
Its particularity is its immense capacity to gather light.
Despite having a comparatively smaller mirror diameter, its capacity is comparable to that of the world's largest mirror telescopes.
With the help of the Arecibo Radio Telescope (Puerto Rico), researchers can explore the universe in search of signals of extraterrestrial life.
The radio telescope has a diameter of 305 meters.
In the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence (SETI for its acronym in English) anyone with a computer can help by providing processing power.
View of the European Southern Observatory (ESO) located in the Chilean Andes.
Here stands the Very Large Telescope, a telescope that lives up to its name.
With a total of four mirrors, this telescope can also illuminate the mid-infrared spectrum.
The ESO will also host the so-called E-ELT (European Extremely Large Telescope).
The primary mirror will span 42 meters and consist of a total of 1,000 reflective elements.
en: It is not expected to be able to take pictures until 2018.
Until 2007, the two Keck telescopes located on the Hawaiian volcano of Mauna Kea were considered the largest in the world.
These have two mirrors, each with a diameter of 10 meters.
The Keck telescopes are part of the Mauna Kea Observatory, which, along with them, explores the sky with the help of the Subaru telescope and the IRTTF.
It is planned to build a new telescope of enormous proportions on Mauna Kea with a thirty-meter mirror diameter.
