The journey through the mountainous region of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus rumbles down the winding road past wooded hills, rushing rivers, and the simple homes of the local farmers.
All is green and juicy, one might even think they are in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost region of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the "Talyshi", a people of whom little is known, apart from their mastery of Persian and Azerbaijani and their long life spans.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts of an architecture perhaps too solid designed in the Soviet era and which does not seem to fit in with such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists hardly come to this place, as the journey from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too strenuous.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers between the two cities because the road is one-way.
The amazing wealth that the country enjoys due to the Caspian Sea oil has yet to reach this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
Baku became famous in May due to the celebration of the Eurovision Festival and next year we will celebrate the Festival of the Elderly People of the World, says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one in the world.
Here is documented the life of eight dozen Talyshis from the area who have lived beyond 100 years of age. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived for 120 years.
One of their sons died at the age of 136.
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheep herder Şirali Müslümov, who appears to have lived for 168 years.
Despite this, there is no birth certificate to certify it.
Taking into account that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, Müslümov's age seems quite suspicious.
Fatulayeva explains that he was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973.
The man had been married three times and had 23 children. Apparently he still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Has Sirali Muslumov been wrong about his age by a couple of decades then?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard about the advanced age of this inhabitant of Central Asia.
In some regions of China, Japan, or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan, there are also people of very advanced age, according to Scholz. Even in Sardinia, there are many elderly men.
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific evidence about the age; especially when there is no civil registry.
Every day glasses filled with melted butter
It is a fact that, surprisingly often, the inhabitants of the region around Lerik tend to reach a biblical age.
Currently there are 20 people who are over 100 years old.
Why do so many elderly people live here in the South?
Azerbaijani tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains that it is about the special genes of the Talyshis.
The director of the museum, Mrs. Fatulayeva, believes instead that the cause lies in nutrition.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem logical that the high-calorie diet of the Talysh, who love meat, bread, and especially dairy products, and many of whom also drink a glass of melted butter daily, is so healthy.
Could it be the natural way of life that keeps people young? In Cengemiran, a small settlement not far from the city of Lerik, Rubaba Mirzayeva lives.
At 97 years old, he is relatively young for what is customary in these parts.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the whole Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor, tirelessly churning an enormous tub of butter.
Eight people live under one roof, including Mirzayeva's son and daughter, both of whom have been grandparents for a long time.
Two small children are also jumping from side to side.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea that is served in typical curved-shaped glasses.
Mirzayeva's teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under her scarf she hides two long braids of dark blonde hair which her son proudly reveals to us.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen out and has kept its color.
Mirzayeva stated, "I have never used shampoo either."
The pension is enough to live on.
He has always only eaten what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes, and peas.
I have never gone grocery shopping at a supermarket in my life.
Then she talks about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst time was the period after World War II.
However, everything returned to normal when the "beloved father", Heydar Aliyev, took control of the situation.
This type of advertising sounds strange coming from an older woman.
However, in Azerbaijan, the cult of the nation's father figure, who rules the country like a dictator, knows no bounds.
He stayed in power until 2003, when he passed the torch to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly people of Azerbaijan do not know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manat (approximately the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount with which one can live well taking into account the situation here.
Maybe Mirzayeva's gray-haired son is right: "In our culture, the elderly are very respected."
They live in a big family, are loved, receive all the necessary care and are happy.
As if this isn't enough reason to stay alive for many years...
