Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
Indeed, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members in a 15-hour overnight session, are truly concerning.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
en: But what does "principles" mean?
This was and remains open to interpretation and it appears that Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal leeway that comes with it, to impose a stricter interpretation of Sharia.
This is at least what is suggested by a new article added: in all matters related to Sharia, it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power throughout Sunni Islam.
It doesn't have to be this way, but this could mean that the clergy would control legislation, something which - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft of the constitution is open to interpretation.
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
Under Mubarak's dictatorship, these courts served to exercise a harsh repression on the opposition.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held in military prisons.
As stipulated in the draft, the State shall protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morality and values".
It is such an imprecise legal formulation that, with the help of this article, state institutions could even control the contents of cinema and literature.
Speaking plainly, it is nothing but censorship.
No article explicitly states equality between men and women.
Instead, another forbids offending or slandering the Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is not clear what constitutes an offense and how it should be sanctioned.
en: Just as dubious is the formulation that prohibits "offense to persons"
Is a cartoon of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
It is a matter of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for his signature and, according to his words, will be presented to the Egyptians "very soon" to be put to a referendum.
English: The revolution has returned.
The opposition has been uniting against the dominance of the Islamists for weeks.
Ten thousand people gathered in an unusual harmony on Friday afternoon in Tahrir Square in Cairo and vowed to make the Act fail before it can come into effect.
en: Hamdin Sabbahi, who is in third place on the presidential election lists, states that "The revolution has returned and we will end up victorious".
English: Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, declared that the draft of the constitution should be "in the dustbin of history".
He accused Morsi's followers of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy" through Twitter.
English: Opponent Jasser Said stated, "When the referendum is called, we will go to his palace and overthrow him."
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers has not yet been avenged," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali.
Several judges announced that they did not wish to oversee the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
en: The Quran is our constitution.
The well-organized Muslim community made a call to hold a counter-demonstration, not in Tahrir Square but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, in front of the University of Cairo.
Many women covered in a veil and supporters of Salafists took part in it, shouting: "The people demand the application of divine law".
They demanded that Morsi "clean up the country," while proclaiming: "the Quran is our constitution."
en: A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where it all began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is evident that supporters of Mursi did not want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim Brotherhood stated that both those who oppose the draft constitution and those who support it had expressed their views loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people decide in the ballot box which direction the country should take.
In this sense, it appears that the draft of the Islamists has a guaranteed majority.
en: "The phrase 'Human Rights' does not even appear."
en: Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process which should have actually lasted until February and included all social forces.
en: This 48-year-old lawyer specialized in human rights and president of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brothers when they were detained in prison or had to face a trial during Mubarak's dictatorship.
He supported Human Rights not because he shared the same ideology, but because for him Human Rights are indivisible.
For this reason, he was beaten, convicted, and imprisoned.
"And now the expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear in the new constitution," laments a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The expansion of Mursi's powers to the three branches of the state caused this lawyer to resign.
en: The measures taken are blatant violations of the rules of democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
Saeda laments that instead of strengthening civil society, the president has abolished it.
en: However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
She feels abandoned, even by the international community, which watches the ideological struggle taking place along the Nile with a mix of curiosity and tension.
This could backfire on you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns, "You are creating a monster you won't be able to control."
